[5] Nebraska (Scotts Bluff County): mixed flock
Date: Wed 6 Apr 2022
Source: Omaha World Herald [edited]
https://bit.ly/3LMrG6K


Highly infectious bird flu has been confirmed in the Nebraska Panhandle, authorities said on Wednesday [6 Apr 2022]. The discovery of ill birds at a farm in Scotts Bluff County is the 5th confirmed case of avian flu among domestic or agricultural flocks in Nebraska, according to the State Department of Agriculture. The 4 other outbreaks have been in the eastern half of the state: Butler, Holt and Merrick counties.

The virus was found in a mixed-species flock numbering fewer than 50 birds, according to the state. All have been euthanized and incinerated. The state agriculture department has established a 6.2 mile surveillance zone around the location, as outlined by USDA policy. This alerts poultry owners to the risk of infection and reminds them to take extra steps to protect their flocks.

Additional cases have been found among wild birds in Nebraska, including in the Lincoln and Omaha areas. The largest Nebraska outbreak has been at 2 industrial-sized poultry operations in Butler County, where a total of 970 000 birds have been euthanized and are in the process of being composted, according to the state. The virus isn't harmful to humans and isn't as deadly among wild birds as it is among domestic birds.

[byline: Nancy Gaarder]

